I’m not lying when I say, I make this pesto pasta salad at least once a week. It’s so simple and delicious, whilst also packed full of veggies! 😍 and most of all, it makes a great “convenience” lunch/ dinner meal for during the busy work week OR meal-prep option. 

Here’s what you need: 
500g Chicken breast/ tenders (I crumbed mine with 1 cup Wholemeal bread crumbs + 2 XL eggs) 
pack of pasta of choice (suggestion: if making a plant-based version- use a pulse pasta for additional protein) 
Pesto sauce of choice 
Heaps of veggies of choice I used a combination of spinach, tomatoes, baby cucumbers, and red onion 
Parmesan cheese (to serve)
+ fresh herbs of choice (optional) 

Method:
1. Cook pasta as per back of packet instructions. Drain and then set aside.

2. Meanwhile, prepare the crumbed chicken breast (if making from scratch or optional lilydale store bought option). Whisk eggs in a medium-sized bowl. On a separate plate, lay out the bread crumbs. Place each chick strip in the egg mixture followed by the bread crumbs, tossing to coat. Place crumbed chicken strips in a lined air-fryer. 3. Meanwhile, prepare and chop vegetables of choice. Place in a large mixing bowl with the cooked pasta, and cooked chicken strips (diced). 

4. Topped with Parmesan cheese & enjoy!

These plate guides are a good guide to get you started if you’re an active individual, trying to optimise your performance. 

All athletes have different nutrition needs for their training based on their sport, body size, the intensity of training, phase of training, and several other factors.

These plates provide a simplified, more- qualitative way to learn how to “fuel” your body, based on an individuals training load and/ lifestyle, incorporating the nutrition priorities:
🍳 Protein - build and repair muscles
🥯 Carbohydrates -“fuel” / energy. Our muscles and brain prefer to use carbohydrates as energy for moderate to higher intensity training. 
🥦 Colour - plants/ fruits & vegetables
for vitamins, minerals and fibre
🫒 Healthy fats - hormone regulation, energy, nutrient absorption, “anti-inflammatory” properties 

One important reason a ✨ performance ✨ plate can optimise performance is by  increasing carbohydrate availability (aka the main “fuel” source for particular training). These plates can also support health and have a role in body composition (i.e building muscle versus fat loss). For the purpose of this post however we will be focussing on the performance perspective. 

A good place to a start is to rate your current plate. Have a look at your current plate and see if it resembles something close to this guide/s. If you’re coming into important training/competition, and you notice your plate looks like more of a “colour” or “balanced plate” focus, adjusting your plate to incorporate more carbs and hence “fuel” for this training/ session will be favourable for your training/ performance.

Some easy ways to incorporate more carbs:
✅ increase portion of rice/pasta/ etc
✅ “fortify” with liquid carbs/ concentrated sources especially for it appetite is low (i.e juice, tomato sauce, etc) 
✅ pair with sides - slice of bread, pita, etc

To put it simply, the more “fuel” is required (aka carbohydrates) the more you play ⚽️🏃🏼‍♀️🏀🚴🏻 🏈🏋🏼‍♀️

*guide only, individual portion sizes will vary. 

**adjusted from The Athlete's Plate® the University of Colorado (UCCS) Sport Nutrition Graduate Program.

Chicken Korma Rice Bowl 🥘

I wish you all could have smelt my kitchen whilst making this 🤤

The smell & taste of this dish is incredible! Definitely a new favourite and a crowd pleaser. 

One of my many favourite things about this dish is the abundance of veggies. 

Here’s what you need:
✨300g pumpkin (puréed, or canned - if making with strath combine with additional ~100mL reduced salt chicken stock) 
✨100ml reduced salt chicken stock 
✨3 cloves garlic 
✨1 small brown onion 
✨Ginger (~1 tbsp crushed) 
✨1 x 400mL can tomato purée 
✨1-2 tbsp korma paste of choice
✨1 tsp cumin 
✨1 tsp paprika 
✨1 tsp turmeric 
✨1/2 tsp chilli flakes (optional) 
✨500g chicken breast, diced 
✨@yoproau plain PERFORM yoghurt 

To serve (optional): 
✨ basmati rice (I used a microwave sachet for convenience)
✨green beans (steamed) 
✨pickled onion 
✨crushed almonds 
✨fresh herbs (i.e coriander)
 ✨lime wedge 
 ✨YoPRO Naan bread - refer to recipe on @yoproau instagram page

Method:
1. In a large frying pan, combine the onion, garlic, and ginger, cooking on low heat until fragrant. 
2. Add in the korma paste and cook for ~1-2 minutes until combined. 
3. Next, add in the diced chicken breast, cooking for ~5 minutes on high heat, until flesh is entirely white on the outside. 
4. Add in the tomato purée and pumpkin purée, mixing to combine, followed by the stock. 
5. Reduce to a simmer, cooking for ~10-15 minutes or until slightly thickened. 
6. Assemble bowls as directed with microwaved rice, chicken korma, additional greens/ veg, fresh herbs, and @yoproau yoghurt! 😍
 
Enjoy!

This 10-minute couscous salad idea (with crispy chickpeas) is a time saver for during the busy work week ⏰ 
 
You can customise it to your own dietary preferences or needs. 
 
Here’s how I made mine:
 
INGREDIENTS: 
1 cup couscous of choice (uncooked, I usually opt for a wholemeal option however I didn’t have this available to me)  
2-3 cups rocket leaves 
1 punnet cherry tomatoes/sundried tomato 
1 cup baby cucumbers, sliced 
1/2 medium yellow capsicum 
1/2 med red onion, finely diced 
1 (400g) can salt reduced chickpeas 
Herbs/ seasonings of choice 
@cobramestate extra virgin olive oil 
Reduced fat fetta, to serve 
 
Dijon vinaigrette:
3 tablespoons @cobram extra virgin olive oil 2 tablespoons white wine vinegar
1 flat teaspoon Dijon 1 heaped tsp honey/ maple syrup  1 teaspoon lemon juice salt & pepper, to season 
 
Your choice to serve with further sides to increase protein content (i.e if not opting for a plant-based recipe) such as:
✅ shredded chicken breast
✅ tinned Tuna (in EVOO, drained) 
✅ lamb, roasted    
 
METHOD:

1.Rinse and drain chickpeas. Season in a medium mixing bowl with extra virgin olive oil and herbs/spices of choice (I used paprika, onion powder, and salt & pepper). Place chickpeas in air fryer train and cook for ~8-10 minutes at 200 degrees Celsius fan forced (or until golden and crispy).

2.Meanwhile prepare the couscous as per the back of packet instructions. 

3.Finely slice & prepare vegetable ingredients of choice. 

4.In a large mixing bowl start to assemble the couscous salad - adding the cooked couscous, rocket leaves, additional sliced veggies, and crispy chickpeas. 

5.Drizzle with Dijon vinaigrette and serve with fresh herbs (I used mint) and fetta (optional). 

6.For an additional protein “boost” - please refer to note above for some suggestions. 
 
Enjoy!! 🫶🏼

Building muscle, whilst maximising strength & performance, involves 2 main priorities from a nutrition perspective:

✅ Fuelling adequately - eating enough energy (calories/kJ) 
✅ Eating enough protein plus distributing this accordingly across the day
 For the purpose of this post we will be focussing on the protein component.  
 
There is no doubt that protein plays an important role in muscle recovery & repair, from making it a key nutrient for individuals involved in resistance training and looking to increase strength. 
 
While total daily protein intake is priority (~1.6-2.2 g/kg/BWT for strength and conditioning individuals), distributing this evenly for 4-6 meals across the day (~0.4-0.55 g/kg/ meal), is also important to allow ample opportunities to reach the leucine threshold and trigger muscle protein synthesis (big fancy words for the process behind ‘building muscle’). Then followed by protein quality and timing.   In sports nutrition, we’re always talking about aiming to nail the cake batter first (i.e. adequate total daily intake), before worrying about the sprinkles (aka timing), so let’s look at this first! 

Using the 65kg athlete as an example, consuming ~100-140g of protein evenly across the day should look like ~26-35g -of protein per meal, unlike what we commonly see where an individual consumes minimal protein at breakfast, a moderate dose at lunch and a generally quite a large dose at dinner time. 

Of course, this is just an example only, as individual requirements and hence recommendations will vary, but more so showing an overview on how to ‘pulse’ your protein intake across the day (should building muscle and performance be your goal) as well as some protein rich meal & snack ideas. 

**dessert is optional in terms of not needed to meet protein requirements, but certainly a must IMO 😉

Whipped yoghurt chocolate mousse 🍫 

OH MY! 🤤 This higher protein mousse tasted like a cross between cheesecake and chocolate mousse. So decadent & delicious! 

Here’s what you need (makes 2):
✨ 2 x tubs @yoproau yoghurt of choice (vanilla or salted caramel go great in this!) 
✨ 2 heaped tsp reduced fat Philadelphia cheese 
✨ 1 tbsp cocoa powder (sifted) 
✨ 1 tbsp sweetener/ honey/ maple or alt of choice (optional) 
✨ 2 tsp gelatin / alt (I.e agar agar) mixed with ~8 tbsp of water 

To serve (optional)
✨ Berries of choice 
✨ Light whipped cream (for something a little bit fancy) 
✨ Sprinkle of cocoa powder 

Method:
1. In a blender, food processor, or similar, combine the yoghurt, Philadelphia cheese, sweetener/alt, and cocoa powder and pulse until smooth. 
2. In a separate small bowl, combine the gelatine & water, mixing with a spoon/ fork to combine. Place in the microwave, heating for 10 seconds increments at a time for 30 seconds total, or until gelatine has dissolved. 
3. Add gelatine to the yoghurt mixture and stir with a spatula to combine. 
4. Pour yoghurt mixture into serving glasses/ containers and refrigerate for ~4-6 hours or until set. 
5. Serve with desired toppings
Enjoy 🫶🏼✨

This is up there with one of my most FAQs and client struggles when it comes to optimising veggie intake whilst also enjoying them at the same time 😅

And it doesn’t surprise me as we consistent research suggesting that a large majority of Australians aren’t meeting the recommended veggie guidelines (of 5-6 serves depending on age & sex). 

I see a lot of clients who come to me suggesting that they don’t like veggies, where sometimes, they just aren’t eating them in a way that sells them. 

Chicken, broccoli, and rice all day every day for a few weeks to months is a sure way to put anyone off veggies. 

My main advice is to experiment and make it ✨ fun ✨ 

We’re allowed to eat food for purposes other just “fuel”.. food is also enjoyment, joy,  pleasure and so much more, and that is a-okay! 

Find ways & veggies that you enjoy and start off slow and build your variety as you go along. 

Some of my favourite ways to
make veg “snazzy”:

1️⃣ Tray bakes/ air fryer bakes (my new obsession) + FLAVOUR - see next point

2️⃣ If adding a bit of salt, sugar, or fat to your veggies increase your desire and therefore ability to eat these, then it’s a MASSIVE nutrition win in a Dietitian’s opinion. 

3️⃣ Get creative and experiment with different recipes in the kitchen- especially ones where you can quite easily add veggies into it (I’m loving pasta salads and ‘throw together bowl’ at the moment). Other examples of easy dishes to boost the veggie intake include soups, curries, ect. 

4️⃣ Find fun ways to add veggies into your meals - a recent favourite is pureeing / blending veggies into sauces/ curries, etc. 

4️⃣ You can still enjoy your favourite meals certainly! If you notice one of your regular meals is quite low in plant based ingredients - add something on the side to enjoy adjust to that meal 🤗

And remember, all veggies, in all forms, are welcome here 🍠🥒🌽🥕🫑🥒

** just a reminder, there is no such thing as the ‘perfect diet’ and if you find a meal here and there isn’t quite “adequate” in terms of veggie content, that is a-okay! 🫶🏼 What matters most is what you do most of the time, not sometimes. Zoom out and take a look at the bigger picture of things!

My running story 👇🏼 

I was a “runner” in my teens, competing in state long distance running events. 

But, what many didn’t realised is that it was fuelled by unhealthy intentions. 

Running became a way to manage an obsessive preoccupation with my weight and fear of weight gain. 

It was used as a means to “earn” and/or “burn” food. 

As a result, I lost my love for running and stopped. 

As you can probably tell, like many individuals, I’ve also been though a rough time with my relationship with food & my body. 

Fast forward a few years, improving my nutrition knowledge and my relationship with food, my body, and training… it’s so nice to finally be in a place where I no longer use running to “punish” my body.

I run because:
👟 I love the challenge it brings. 
👟 It’s motivating. 
👟 It’s social connection. 
👟 It makes me feel truely freakin amazing (if any of you have ever experienced a “runners high” you’ll get what I mean 😉). 

Don’t get me wrong, some days I have a love hate relationship with running and don’t enjoy no where near as much, however, Its a way that keeps me moving and motivated, AND it no longer fuelled by unhealthy motivations and/or “self sabotage”. 

Here is your reminder to move your body in ways that makes you feel your best, and for all the other positive health benefits and reasons, other than “earning” food or as a form of “punishment”. 

You never have to earn food. Food is fuel for life 🫶🏼

How to gauge if you are eating ✨enough ✨to support your health & performance 👀 
Of course there are more quantitative ways to measure energy input versus output, however for the purpose of this post, I have focussed on more qualitative ways that you can to access yourself to gauge your current nutrition strategy, and whether this is serving you, or not. 
 A lot of what I have spoken about when it comes to “underfuelling” or low energy availability (LEA) has been a focus on the loss/ abnormalities in menstruation function in females. However, it is important to note that LEA does not discriminate. Anybody - men & women can experience LEA.   Along with a menstrual cycle changes and alterations to libido, there are also a list of other interrelated physiological/ qualitative measures that we can pay attention to & monitor, such as:   ➡️ energy levels  ➡️ concentration & productivity  ➡️ performance & recovery  ➡️ frequent illness/prone to injuries  ➡️ sleep quality, etc  Plus many more!   Of course if you are experiencing one or a collection of these doesn’t necessarily mean that you are in a LEA state, as many of these can also coincide with other medical diagnoses (i.e. digestive concerns, menstrual irregularities, etc), however they are definitely red flags/ cues that should be explored further with the help from a Sports Dietitian particularly if multiple are present, and/or you have a high training load 👟

It’s finally winter (in Aus), and I’m normally a massive overnight oats fan due 1) convenience, 2) the endless flavour possibilities, and 3) it’s nourishing, however its a touch too cold for that (IMO), and my normal porridge just wasn’t doing it for me, so I’ve put a fun little spin on my original oatmeal recipe 🤤

This recipe also makes a great meal prep recipe also for those busy mid-weeks mornings also ✅ 

And another bonus: it also uses up those ripe bananas that you may have lying around 🍌 

Here’s how to make your own:
INGREDIENTS (Makes ~6 slices)
3 cups oats of choice (2 cups whole & 1 cup oat flour) 
2 large ripe bananas, mashed 
1 1/2 cups milk of choice 
1/4 cup honey/ maple/ sweetener of choice 
1 1/2 tsp baking powder 
Scoop protein powder (optional) 
2 heaped tbsp nut butter/ LSA meal 
3 tbsp cocoa powder 
Chocolate of choice - I used 6 squares of 
@lindt dark chocolate pieces on top

Serve with:
@yoproau vanilla/ salted caramel yoghurt 
Thawed raspberries / alt fruit of choice 
Additional but butter, if desired. 

Method:
1. Preheat oven to 180 degrees Celsius (fan forced). In a blender combine 1/3 of the oats and process until a fine meal forms. 
2. Transfer oat flour and whole oats into a medium mixing bowl. Add in the banana (mashed), cocoa powder, nut butter/ LSA meal, baking powder, protein powder (optional), maple/honey, and milk of choice. 
3. Mixing with a spatula until well combined and then transfer mixture into a lined sheet pan/tray, spreading across the base of the on to evenly distribute. Place chopped pieces of chocolate on top. 
4. Place in the oven and bake for ~15-20 minutes or until firm to touch. 
5. Refrigerate until ready to serve (i.e each morning) or slice up and transfer into individual containers - your choice here 🥰Serve warm (or microwaved for ~1 minutes the next morning) with serving suggestions. 

**Store in the refrigerator. Individual portion sizes will vary. 

Enjoy ❤️‍🔥

CHEAT SHEET 🔥: calcium rich foods/ products

Calcium is essential for optimal bone health & function plus other important roles. 

Dietary calcium needs to remain sufficient for these functions to be maintained optimally longer-term. 

Optimal bone health, from a nutrition perspective involves adequate ‘fuel’ - i.e. energy availability to support bone & hormonal function, plus calcium and vitamin D intake. 

Some athletes at risk of inadequate calcium intake and subsequent poor bone health include those with: 

🚩 Low calcium intakes or inadequate intake of dairy and/or calcium fortified dairy products
🚩 Some vegetarian and/or vegan athletes
🚩Inadequate fuelling due to inadequate knowledge or disordered eating practices - i.e. excessive dietary restriction coupled with over-training. 
🚩 impaired menstrual function 
🚩Poor calcium balance due to undiagnosed/ poorly managed gut conditions

How can we support our bone health and ensure we’re eating enough?

🦴 majority of our calcium intake of a western diet comes from dairy products or calcium fortified alternatives, with smaller amounts from fish, legumes, nuts, etc. 

The easiest way to ensure you’re meeting recommended calcium intakes would be to aim for ~2.5-3 serves of dairy per day (depending on the individuals age, etc) 

A serve is classified as: 🥛 1 cup milk / calcium fortified alt  🧀 2 x slices or 40g cheese  🍶 1 pot or ~170-200g yoghurt  *depending on the yoghurt 

For individuals not consuming dairy for  either intolerance and/or ethical or environmental reasonings, an easy win for these individuals is to swap to a calcium fortified plant based milk (i.e. Vitasoy Calciplus as picture). By doing this alone, almost contributed to half of your daily calcium intake, if having the full serve as specified (~1 cup).

This apple & cinnamon baked oatmeal is a perfect nourishing winter warmer recipe ❄️ It also makes a great meal prep recipe for those busy work weeks 😍

Here now to make your own: 
INGREDIENTS (Makes ~6 slices)
✨ 3 cups oats of choice (2 cups rolled & 1 cup oat flour) 
✨ 1 scoop protein powder (optional - I used @colessupermarkets Perform Elite plant range - vanilla flavour)
✨ 1 1/2 cup milk of choice 
✨ 1 1/2 tsp baking powder
✨ 2 small apples, diced (1 1/5 in mixture and 1/2 as a ‘garnish’) 
✨2 tbsp LSA meal OR 2 tbsp nut butter of choice 
✨ 1 flat tsp cinnamon spice 
✨ 1/4 cup honey/ maple/ SF maple of choice

@yoproau salted caramel yoghurt 
Berries/ fruit of choice 
Additional crushed nuts/ nut butter

This air-fryer baked shakshuka eggs might just be my new favourite b’fast creation and winter warmer ☃️thanks to @emmaclaire_nutrition for this awesome airfryer eggs hack! 

Packed full of flavour, it’s a perfectly balanced combo of veggies, protein, wholegrains and healthy fats. 
For my savoury peeps, this one if for you! 

RECIPE (serves 1):
✨ 1 cup tinned tomatoes 
✨ 1/4 small onion, diced
✨ 1/2 small capsicum (I used red) 
✨ 1/2 tsp garlic paste 
✨ 1 tsp paprika
✨ 1/2 tsp cumin
✨ 1/2 tsp chilli flakes (optional)
✨ 1/8 cup water (or as needed)
✨ 2 XL eggs 
✨ Fresh herbs if choice (I used parsley & coriander) 
✨ YoPRO plain yoghurt (I mixed @yoproau normal yoghurt with lemon juice to create a softer consistency)
✨ Extra virgin olive oil
✨ Seeded sourdough, to serve

Method:
1. Line an airfryer tray with baking paper (or optional to place into a dish that fits within your air-fry). Place some extra virgin olive oil (EVOO), tinned tomatoes, diced capsicum & red onion, followed by the spices, into the base of the fryer / dish. Mix with a touch of water until well combined. 
2. Cook for ~10-15 minutes at 180 degrees celsius until the veggies are soft. 
3. Make two wells with a spoon and place an egg in each. Add more water if needs here. Cook again for ~5-10 minutes, on the same temperature, or until desired egg texture is achieved. 
4. Serve with @yoproau plain yoghurt (see optional note above), a drizzle of EVOO (optional), herbs of choice, and toasted bread of choice. 
Enjoy!! 🫶🏼

Many people approach their personal health and/or nutrition goals from an all-or-nothing thinking lens 👀   All-or-nothing thinking makes those feel “stuck” and in a constantly “yo-yo” from one extreme to another, such as:   🍴 constantly changing from “diet” to “diet” 🍩 alternating from restriction to binge 👟 not doing any exercise to over-training 😔 feeling motivated and excited to feeling like you’ve “fallen off the wagon”   When you feel as though your nutrition isn’t “perfect” or that there are multiple barriers in the way, aim for something “in-between”. 

It doesn’t have to be “all” or “nothing” or “good” or “bad”. Nutrition is a spectrum.   See point for more details & tips ❤️‍🔥

Today I completed my 3rd half marathon attempt, and although it wasn’t my best run, after recently recovering from influenza (which I must say knocked me about for a few solid weeks), I had a ball and enjoyed the process nevertheless. Plus bonding with people over a sport and making new friends is pretty dang cool 😎 

One really cool thing I got to experiment with this one in particular was a legitimate carb load, and not just a big bowl of pasta the night before an event type of carb load 😂 

If you’ve ever completed a carb load before (~10-12 g/kg/ BWT of carbohydrates) you would appreciate that this is A LOT of carbs which comes with its own unique challenges. 

Things that I trialled throughout the process which I found super useful: 

 ✅ The use of fluids as a vehicle to deliver carbohydrate without additional food volume (i.e maltodextrin combined with water) +/- fruit juices, sports drinks, soft drinks, etc. 

✅ Making use of very compact carbohydrate sources or “simple carbs”. Simple carbs are very useful during this phase as trying to meet these carbohydrate requirements through “whole foods” alone can be challenging, especially those of higher body mass and hence requirements. 

✅ Minimise fibre, fat and protein intakes (relative to your requirements to ensure you can ‘fit’ enough carbs in) 

**Again, this is a situation where general healthy eating is different to sports nutrition principles. And that’s okay! 

It’s safe to say from a performance perspective I felt great - I carried myself for much longer this half marathon attempt, with the assistance of intra- race “fuel” also (I.e carbohydrate gels, etc), whilst still feeling reasonable by the 15km point. 

Today was yet another example of how freakin’ cool nutrition science really is 😍

A different perspective on “pre-workout”, from a sports dietitian 🤔 

This post is not neglecting the use of pre-workouts, as it’s a case by case scenario, and some people might: 
a) not like the taste of coffee
b) like the convenience these options provide 
plus c) like the fact that they can exactly quantify how much caffeine they’re getting (over a coffee for example which can vary in caffeine content), however you certainly don’t “need” one is my point.

In a lot of cases it may be more effective to isolate certain supplements (i.e creatine and beta alanine) and take these separately to ensure you’re getting enough, and consistently every day also (as it’s potentially unlikely you’ll take your pre workout 7 days a week, and consistency is key to keep up saturation levels). 

The thing I find is that most people substitute inadequate energy intake with caffeine. Picture caffeine like a band-aid for an underlying inadequate diet.

Rather than getting home and just having pre-workout before your training session/s, try combining this, or caffeine, with some simple “performance” carbs prior and see how this makes you feel 😋

All just food for thought ❤️‍🔥

A performance enhancing supplement that most people are consuming, without even potentially realising, is caffeine 🐐 

Although, the main area of influence is that some individuals might not be consuming enough, and at the right time, to elicit performance benefits (i.e a 70kg female having a black coffee prior to a morning training session ~80mg which can also have a large variability depending on outlet purchases/ source, where really they may require ~200mg* to elicit performance enhancements, that’s if performance is their goal of course. 

I spoke about Caffeine last week but it primarily inhibits adenosine receptor/s essentially “blocking” feelings of tiredness. Caffeine also stimulates adrenaline production, increasing “flight” or “fight”. 

From a training perspective, at lower doses, caffeine can reduce the perception of effort of training, and at higher doses may improve performance, such as:
⬆️ in 1 deletion max & 
⬆️ in repetitions to failure 

Current recommendations for caffeine intake (30-60 minutes prior to training): 

⏰ Alertness/ Wakefulness: 1-3mg/kg of body weight. This amount typically does not enhance performance but can reduced the perfection of effort of training (i.e training essentially “feels easier”). 

👟 Performance (including both endurance and power): in practice, ~3-6mg/kg* of body weight is the gold standard

Although not a comprehensive list, this cheat sheet aims to highlight the different caffeine content of foods, in particular common “sports nutrition” foods/ supplements and how you could optimise your intake (i.e though caffeine rich options and/or a combination). 

*individual variance & preference occurs. The amount specific to you will be determined based on your individual tolerance, metabolism, and medical history, whilst also considering the impact on sleep. Work with a professional to work out a tailored plan appropriate and safe for you.

One of the easiest places to start when trying to change/ improve your relationship with food is reflecting and changing your language around food and/or how you perceive food. 

Labels such as good and bad carry moral connotations. 

While there are many ethical concerns related to food and nutrition, foods by itself cannot be ‘virtuous’. 

Foods have many characteristics that influence their overall nutritional value, especially when eaten by certain people with particular circumstances.. you could ‘nit pick’ almost any food and/or it’s nutrients, however, the context and dose is important. 

Therefore, labelling foods as either good or bad is simplistic & inaccurate. This includes fear mongering - i.e. labelling foods as ‘toxic’ (unless the food is contaminated or mouldy of course 😉) 

The bottom line is that much of the language around food and nutrition that is promoted today, particularly in the online space, traps us into a reductionist, all-or-nothing way of thinking.

This ultimately prevents us from achieving true well-being, as well as specific goals. 

Next time you catch yourself using these types of words (pictured), take a moment to reflect, and consider the bigger, more nuanced picture of nutrition & health ✨

It’s more than okay to take a break, and allow your body to rest & rejuvenate 🫶🏼

Of course, it’s important from a general health perspective to move our body’s regularly, but it’s also important to acknowledge intentions, and when the body needs rest. 

Far too often I see individuals leading a high training load/ very active lifestyle/ and/or a combination of the two, and not eating enough to meet these demands, leading to underfuelling and it’s cascade of negative health and performance effects 🚩

Let’s zoom out and take a look at the bigger picture of health. Health is an average of daily habits.. not one single food or workout. 

Take a break. Your body does great, productive things when it rests. 

And just because you aren’t training, that doesn’t mean you don’t “deserve” to eat either. The amount of energy that you utilise during a training session is a small fraction of the total energy that you require in order to thrive, function, and complete daily activities. 

Irrespective, you never have to “earn” food. Food is “fuel” for life my friends 🤝

Holy smokes 🔥 these olive oil cookies are so soft/ velvety/ crumby/ delicious/ everything… they might just be my new favorite !! 

If you haven’t tried adding extra virgin olive oil to your cookies yet, consider this your sign to give them a go 😉 also, if you’re yet to add some ground coffee to your cookies, consider this even more of a sign. A literal game changer! 

Ingredients (makes 15-16): 
1/2 cup cup extra virgin olive oil
1 tsp pure vanilla extract
1/4 cup granulated sugar
1/2 cup golden brown sugar
1 flat tsp coffee ground (optional) 
Pinch salt, plus xtra for garnish
1 large egg
2-2.5 cups plain flour 
1/2 teaspoon baking powder 
Chocolate of choice

Method:
1. Preheat oven to 180 degrees Celsius (fan forced). Combine the olive oil, sugar, and vanilla, into a medium mixing bowl. Pulse with an electric struck blender to combine (this gets rid of lumps and bumps). 
2. Add in a whisked egg, storing with a all’aula to combine. 
3. Sift in the flour with the baking powder, and then finally add in your favourite coffee ground (optional but necessary in my opinion 😉).

5. Roll into balls and then place on lined baking tray. Bake for ~12-14 minutes or until slightly golden. 

Enjoy my friends 🫶🏼

As the festive season approaches us (crazy, I know 🤯), here is your reminder that nutrition and “health” does not have to be “all or nothing”. 

Typically I hear oh I can’t have that chocolate/ biscuit/ cake/ pasta/ bread.. as that’s “bad” or “unhealthy”, but in reality there are no “good” or “bad” foods. Nutrition (& health) are a spectrum. Let’s detach the “good” and “bad” morale from food.

Nutrition doesn’t have to be “perfect”. What matters more for your health is what you do on the remaining days/weeks/ months of the year, rather than a day, two, or three of celebration..

This post aims to bring awareness and a “snapshot” consuming enough carbohydrates to compliment your training load and hence support your performance (should that be your goal). 

Every time I show this table to clients in clinic, I’m always astound by the amount of individuals that say “wow that’s a lot of carbs”. And you’re not alone if you’re also thinking this whilst reading this post 👀 

The reality is, a lot of athletes (everyday to elite) undershoot their carbohydrate requirements. 

And as you may spot, as carbohydrate needs increase, the need to equip more “easy to digest” and “efficient” carbs can be useful (i.e sauces, honey, juice, etc). Especially for those who may struggle to eat “enough” in terms of food volume and or may have a reduced appetite (i.e post training). 

Of course, their baseline diet is nutritious and contains whole-foods where appropriate, however, this is why as sports Dietitians you may hear us talking about how general healthy eating and performance nutrition are two different concepts. 

And as as a lot of posts on social media highlight what “x” amount of protein looks like in a day, but carbs are just, if not more of an MVP 😎, in a sports dietitians opinion. 

Whilst carbohydrates are key to support performance (particularly moderate to high intensity training, and/or endurance in nature), let’s not neglect total daily energy intake, which reflects macronutrient requirements (carbohydrates, protein, and fats). 

This post also does not factor in individual’s day to day fuelling needs, however, which can change across different days of the week or a training cycle. 

If you’re in need of some “fuelling” assistance please don’t hesitate to reach out and enquire about 1:1 nutrition support 🔥 

*These requirements are guidelines principally determined by their training load (the intensity x frequency x duration of training) and body mass. Use them at your own individual discretion.

🍽️ Have you ever found yourself feeling 'guilty' about your food choices or caught up in the 'good' vs 'bad’ dilemma?   Cue: Positive Food Language! 🌟 
What exactly is Positive Food Language? 🗣️ It's a way of discussing food without attaching ‘shame’ or ‘guilt’ based on the perceived ‘healthiness’ of a food/ group. 

But why does language matter? 🤔 

The way we talk about food and the moral value we attached to food can have a big impact on our relationship with food.   Research suggests the language that we use around food can have a profound impact on our emotions, influencing our food choices and attitudes. Associating foods with “guilt” can harm our relationship with them. 

For instance, a study found that those associating chocolate cake with 'guilt' felt less control and had a less positive attitude toward eating healthily than those associating it with 'celebration.'  So how to talk about food? Keep it neutral. 

Recognise that  food plays a larger role in our lives than a simple biological necessity. 

Then, remove the labels and added ‘moral value’ that comes with common ‘diet culture’ language. 

Describe foods by what they are without categorising them as being ‘good’, ‘bad’, ‘clean’, ‘skinny’, ‘junk’, or ‘detoxing’, etc. 

AND use non-diet descriptors like 'satisfying,' 'pleasurable,' ‘nutritious’, or 'delicious' instead of 'naughty' or a ‘guilty pleasure’. 

Of course, there is a spectrum when it comes to food and nutrition, where there are more nutritious and less nutritious foods, however, the key word is spectrum (and context!). There shouldn’t be ‘moral value’ attached to food. 
 Becoming aware of the words you use is the first step. It takes time, but the first step is recognising and then changing these habits 🫶🏼

This post may not be new information for those who have quite some knowledge and understanding in nutrition, however for others, this may offer value.

One key thing I love to highlight to clients is that yes, whilst some foods may be ‘sources’ of protein, they may not be the ‘best’ or more ‘efficient’. 

What this means is that some foods, such as some dairy options, and for a large majority of plant proteins, you often need a large quantify of this food, to reach an ideal protein amount (which is specific to the individual and their requirements). 

This may not be an issue for those who:  1) have large energy requirements  2) touching on from this, have a larger appetite anyhow.

And so if you fall into this ‘not so favourable’ category above, learning how to maximise your intake, by choosing more ‘efficient’ sources, may just benefit you.

 To serve (optional)  Raspberries go AMAZING with this 🤭

Method:
1. heat oven to 180 degrees Celsius (~350 degrees Fahrenheit). 

2.In a greased oven safe container/baking tray (15-20x15-20), combine banana, mashing this like so, followed by the rolled oats, vanilla protein powder OR wholemeal plain flour*, baking powder, honey/maple, olive oil, coffee, and milk. Mix until well combined.

3.Place in the oven and cook for about ~35-40 minutes, or until golden and firm to touch.

4.Allow oats to cool completely in the container/ tray, and then loosen the edges with a knife and then combine and add the yoghurt ‘topping’, followed by the cocoa powder, and then refrigerate. 

5.Upon serving the next day, cut into ~4 servings*. If serving warm the next day - reheat a slice in the microwave for ~1 minute (yes the yoghurt layer actually tastes great slightly heated also, or you can add this the next day, after heating if you would prefer), or serve as is/cold.

*individual portion sizes will vary. If opting for the no protein powder option, serve with an additional heaped tbsp or two of yoghurt (depending on yoghurt brand), per serve/slice, to ensure a similar protein serve too option A.
